    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly, I apologize for the confusion. In the context of a real estate transaction, the escrow agent is a neutral third party responsible for holding and disbursing funds according to the terms of the escrow agreement. Legally, the escrow agent must follow the instructions provided in the escrow instructions, which are part of the purchase agreement.\n\nIf there's a dispute about the funds, the escrow agent is bound by the escrow agreement and must act impartially. They cannot release the funds until the dispute is resolved or until the terms of the escrow agreement are fulfilled. In some cases, the escrow agent may be required to hold the funds in a separate account until the dispute is resolved. If the dispute cannot be resolved, it may need to be taken to court, and a judge will make a decision based on the terms of the escrow agreement and applicable laws.\n\nThe escrow agent's responsibilities include:\n\n1. Receiving the funds from the buyer and holding them securely.\n2. Disbursing the funds to the seller once the terms of the escrow agreement are met.\n3. Providing a detailed accounting of all transactions to both the buyer and seller.\n4. Acting impartially and in accordance with the escrow agreement.\n\nThe escrow agent's role is crucial in ensuring a fair and",
      "source": "target",
